<b>MK-DOS</b> - one of the most wide-spread <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../194/22194.xml">
operating system</link>s for <computer wordnetid="103082979" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../329/169329.xml">
Elektronika BK</link></computer>
 <system wordnetid="108435388" confidence="0.8">
<economy wordnetid="108366753" confidence="0.8">
<group wordnetid="100031264" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../779/26779.xml">
Soviet</link></group>
</economy>
</system>
 personal computer, developed by Mikhail Korolev and Dmitriy Butyrskiy starting from 1993. Like <O wordnetid="106832680" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../322/169322.xml">
ANDOS</link></O>
, the system provided full compatibility of operating environment for all models of BK, emulating environment of BK-0010 on more modern BK-0011 and BK-0011M. All requests to a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../505/20505.xml">
magnetic tape</link> from programs if they were made through proper ROM funcrions were redirected to a disk.<p>

The system supported up to 4 physical disk drives (the number actually limited by disk ROM installed) and as many as number of letters in Latin alphbet <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../777/13777.xml">
hard disk</link> <system wordnetid="104377057" confidence="0.8">
<artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<instrumentality wordnetid="103575240" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../380/55380.xml">
partitions</link></instrumentality>
</artifact>
</system>
 used as separate logical drives with volume of each up to 32 MB (<it>See also: <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../424/55424.xml">
drive letter assignment</link></it>). Starting from version 3.0 the system also supported mounting disk images as <system wordnetid="104377057" confidence="0.8">
<artifact wordnetid="100021939" confidence="0.8">
<instrumentality wordnetid="103575240" confidence="0.8">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../380/55380.xml">
logical drives</link></instrumentality>
</artifact>
</system>
. When booted on BK-0011 or BK-0011M the system automatically created a <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../349/55349.xml">
RAM disk</link> in the computer's memory.</p>
<p>

MK-DOS used a wide-spread on BK MicroDOS <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../280/1010280.xml">
file system</link> which did not support <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../369/3909369.xml">
file fragmentation</link> (like the file system used with <O wordnetid="106832680" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../309/69309.xml">
RT-11</link></O>
). While incompatible with RT-11's file system it shared many principles with it. MicroDOS file system had read-only support in ANDOS. The filename length was limited by 14 symbols (the <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../957/147957.xml">
filename extension</link> was not recognized separately and was considered as a part of the filename).</p>
<p>

Minimum installation of the system took not more than 8 KB of computer's memory. The system had functional graphic <software wordnetid="106566077" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../407/873407.xml">
Norton Commander</link></software>
-like <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../382/11382.xml">
file manager</link> called <it>MCommander</it>. The system shipped with a number of utilities including <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../937/18943937.xml">
emulator</link>s for RT-11, <link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../045/53045.xml">
FAT 12</link> and <O wordnetid="106832680" confidence="0.9508927676800064">
<link xlink:type="simple" xlink:href="../772/10997772.xml">
CSI-DOS</link></O>
 file systems as add-ons for the file manager.</p>

